### File Structure
```
newsportal/
│
├── app.py
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── article_catalog.html
│   ├── article_details.html
│   ├── bookmarks.html
│   ├── comments.html
│   ├── write_comment.html
│   ├── trending_articles.html
│   ├── category.html
│   └── search_results.html
│
├── static/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── styles.css
│   ├── js/
│   │   └── scripts.js
│   └── images/
│       └── (optional thumbnails or icons)
│
└── data/
    ├── articles.txt
    ├── categories.txt
    ├── bookmarks.txt
    ├── comments.txt
    └── trending.txt
```

### File Descriptions
- **app.py**  
  The main Python backend application file. It will handle routing for all nine pages, data reading and writing from/to the local text files in the `data/` directory, and business logic such as searching, filtering, bookmarking, commenting, and tracking trending articles. Since the application is not very complex, consolidating backend logic into this single file is efficient and maintainable.

- **templates/**  
  This directory contains all HTML template files for rendering the frontend pages using a Python web framework (e.g., Flask). Each HTML file corresponds to one of the nine pages specified in the requirements, containing the defined elements with their respective IDs for frontend interaction.

- **static/**  
  Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files for client-side interactivity, and images (e.g., article thumbnails or icons). Organizing these assets separately keeps the project clean and modular.

- **data/**  
  Stores all application data in text files as specified. These files hold articles, categories, bookmarks, comments, and trending data in the defined pipe-separated format. The backend reads from and writes to these files to persist user interactions and content updates.

This structure supports clear separation of concerns, ease of maintenance, and aligns with the project requirements for a Python-based web application managing data via local text files.
